Use mdy dates|date=July 2017
"You Wouldn't Steal a Car" is the first sentence of a propaganda public service announcement|PSA which is part of an anti piracy campaign "Piracy. It's a crime." It was created by the Federation Against Copyright Theft in cooperation with the Intellectual Property Office of Singapore in July 2004,<ref name=IPOS04>cite web|url=http://www.ipos.gov.sg/main/newsroom/media_rel/mediarelease1_270704.html |title=Be HIP at the Movies |author= |date=July 27, 2004 |work=Intellectual Property Office of Singapore |accessdate=March 6, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924044120/http://www1.ipos.gov.sg/main/newsroom/media_rel/mediarelease1_270704.html |archivedate=September 24, 2008 </ref><ref name=Rohrer09>cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/8106805.stm |title=Getting inside a downloader's head |author=Finlo Rohrer |date=June 18, 2009 |work=BBC |accessdate=March 6, 2013</ref> and appeared on many commercial DVDs as either a skippable or unskippable clip before a film is shown. 

It shows a man committing theft of various objects, and compares these crimes with the Copyright infringement|unauthorized duplication and distribution of copyrighted materials, such as films.<ref>cite web|author=Sophia Harris |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/netflix-piracy-content-downloading-copyright-1.4043163 |title=Netflix's anti-piracy team aims to make stealing content uncool - Business - CBC News |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=March 28, 2017 |accessdate=July 6, 2017</ref><ref>cite web|last=Poon |first=Christopher |url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/you-wouldnt-steal-a-car-but-id-download-one/Content?oid=2546900 |title='You wouldn't steal a car,' but I'd download one &#124; Dot Comrade &#124; Pique Newsmagazine &#124; Whistler, CANADA |publisher=Pique Newsmagazine |date= |accessdate=July 6, 2017</ref>

In popular culture
''The IT Crowd'' episode "Moss and the German" spoofed this advert near the start of the episode.

In an episode of ''The Amazing World Of Gumball'', entitled "The DVD", Darwin conveys the information to Gumball after he was about to download a movie named ''Alligators on a Train''. The Greens-European Free Alliance, in association with Rafilm, released their own version of the film to oppose the media industry and government views on existing copyright laws, as well as to educate the public on alternative views about intellectual property.<ref>cite web|title=I would't steal|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211122958/http://www.iwouldntsteal.net:80/|website=iwouldntsteal.net|publisher=The Greens-European Free Alliance|accessdate=25 April 2018</ref><ref>cite web|title=I wouldn't steal <video>|url=https://creativecommons.org/2008/01/26/i-wouldnt-steal-video/|website=creativecommons.org|publisher=The Greens-Eurpean Free Alliance|accessdate=25 April 2018</ref>

The Juice Media produced a controversial parody of this video for Australia Day in 2017. The video compared the celebration of Australia Day, which marks the arrival of the First Fleet, to a number of infamous events in history. The events depicted include Nazism|Nazis' "Final Solution", dropping of the Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|atomic bomb on Hiroshima and September 11 attacks|Sep 11 attacks on the Twin Towers.<ref>Citation|last=thejuicemedia|title=Australia Day (Piracy parody)|date=2017-01-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UytdM-x3cv4|access-date=2018-06-17</ref><ref>Cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/lanesainty/this-video-compares-the-settling-of-australia-to-911-hiroshi|title=This Video Compares Australian Settlement To 9/11, Hiroshima And The Holocaust|work=BuzzFeed|access-date=2018-06-17|language=en</ref>

